    "eyebrow": "Settlement Patterns",
    "num": "02",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">02</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Settlement Patterns</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Geographic Distribution of Texican Settlements</h2><ul><li>Settlements concentrated along rivers: Brazos, Colorado, and Guadalupe</li><li>Land grants often clustered to form colonies with shared cultural ties</li><li>Proximity to Native American territories influenced settlement locations</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican settlements were strategically located near water sources for agriculture and transportation. Clustering of land grants fostered community cohesion but also brought settlers into contact and conflict with Native tribes (s7, s9). <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Austin’s colony was established along the Brazos River, providing fertile land and access to trade routes.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Examine a settlement map and identify how geography influenced Texican colony locations.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Overlooking the importance of rivers and natural resources in settlement choices.</p></div></div>",
