      "h": "Deep Dive: From Settlement to Political Identity",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Understanding Texican settlement and lifestyle provides a foundation for exploring their political and cultural roles in Texas history (s7, s8, s9).</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from lauriemooremoore.com; tshaonline.org; thestoryoftexas.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Settlement patterns influenced political tensions leading to Texas Revolution</li><li>Cultural blending shaped Texican identity and alliances</li><li>Frontier challenges fostered resilience and community cohesion</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>The concentration of Anglo settlers under Mexican law set the stage for later demands for autonomy.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Reflect on how settlement experiences might influence Texican political actions.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Separating settlement history from political developments in Texas.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> lauriemooremoore.com; tshaonline.org; thestoryoftexas.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p>"
