    "id": "slide25",
    "eyebrow": "Cultural Identity",
    "num": "13",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">13</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Cultural Identity</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Blended Anglo-American and Mexican Influences</h2><ul><li>Texicans emerged from a fusion of Anglo-American settlers and Mexican residents</li><li>Cultural practices included language, religion, and legal traditions from both heritages</li><li>This blend shaped unique Texican customs distinct from either Anglo or Mexican alone</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican identity was not purely Anglo or Mexican but a hybrid shaped by intermarriage, shared customs, and bilingualism. This cultural blending influenced daily life, governance, and social norms in early Texas. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texican families often spoke both Spanish and English at home and celebrated Catholic and Protestant holidays, reflecting their dual heritage.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify examples of cultural blending in your own community or family history.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming Texicans were simply Anglo settlers or Mexican nationals without recognizing their hybrid identity.</p></div></div>",
    "paper": {
      "secnum": "Deep Dive 13",
      "h": "Understanding Texican Cultural Hybridity",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texican identity was not purely Anglo or Mexican but a hybrid shaped by intermarriage, shared customs, and bilingualism. This cultural blending influenced daily life, governance, and social norms in early Texas.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Texicans emerged from a fusion of Anglo-American settlers and Mexican residents</li><li>Cultural practices included language, religion, and legal traditions from both heritages</li><li>This blend shaped unique Texican customs distinct from either Anglo or Mexican alone</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Texican families often spoke both Spanish and English at home and celebrated Catholic and Protestant holidays, reflecting their dual heritage.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Identify examples of cultural blending in your own community or family history.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming Texicans were simply Anglo settlers or Mexican nationals without recognizing their hybrid identity.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p>"
    }
