      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Secondary narratives synthesize multiple perspectives, helping learners grasp the complexity and contested nature of Texican cultural identity and political roles.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Historians highlight the fluid and contested nature of Texican identity</li><li>Narratives emphasize both cooperation and conflict within Texican communities</li><li>Secondary sources contextualize primary accounts and broaden understanding</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>A historian’s analysis explains how Texican identity evolved amid shifting political landscapes and demographic changes.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Compare a secondary narrative with a primary source letter to identify points of agreement and difference.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Taking secondary narratives as definitive without considering their interpretive nature.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p>"
