      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Addressing misconceptions prevents oversimplification and promotes a more accurate understanding of Texican cultural and political complexity.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Texicans were not simply Mexican or Anglo settlers but a distinct hybrid group</li><li>Their identity was fluid and evolved over time, not static</li><li>Internal divisions were significant and shaped political outcomes</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Clarifying that Texicans’ bilingualism and biculturalism were central, not peripheral, to their identity.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Reflect on any preconceived notions you had about Texicans and how this lesson has challenged them.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Applying modern labels or assumptions anachronistically to historical groups.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p>"
