    "eyebrow": "Political Alliances",
    "num": "25",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">25</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Political Alliances</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Texican Alliances within Mexican Texas</h2><ul><li>Texicans initially allied with Mexican authorities to secure land and political rights</li><li>Empresarios like Stephen F. Austin acted as intermediaries between Texicans and Mexican government</li><li>Alliances were pragmatic, balancing loyalty to Mexico with local autonomy desires</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texicans formed political alliances with Mexican authorities primarily to gain land grants and legal recognition. Empresarios facilitated these relationships, but Texicans maintained a cautious stance, seeking to protect their interests while navigating Mexican governance (s2, s7). <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Stephen F. Austin negotiated land grants with Mexican officials, enabling Anglo settlers to establish colonies under Mexican law.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Consider why Texicans might have supported Mexican authority initially despite cultural differences. What benefits did this alliance provide?</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming Texicans were always opposed to Mexican rule ignores their early cooperative political strategies.</p></div></div>",
    "paper": {
      "secnum": "Deep Dive 25",
      "h": "Nuances of Texican-Mexican Political Alliances",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texicans formed political alliances with Mexican authorities primarily to gain land grants and legal recognition. Empresarios facilitated these relationships, but Texicans maintained a cautious stance, seeking to protect their interests while navigating Mexican governance (s2, s7).</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Texicans initially allied with Mexican authorities to secure land and political rights</li><li>Empresarios like Stephen F. Austin acted as intermediaries between Texicans and Mexican government</li><li>Alliances were pragmatic, balancing loyalty to Mexico with local autonomy desires</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Stephen F. Austin negotiated land grants with Mexican officials, enabling Anglo settlers to establish colonies under Mexican law.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Consider why Texicans might have supported Mexican authority initially despite cultural differences. What benefits did this alliance provide?</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming Texicans were always opposed to Mexican rule ignores their early cooperative political strategies.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p>"
    }
