      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> This exercise engages learners in synthesizing political events and understanding their impact on Texican history through timeline construction (s2, s7).</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Use provided events to build a timeline of Texican political developments</li><li>Analyze how each event influenced Texican political strategies</li><li>Discuss the progression from alliance to revolution</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Placing the 1830 immigration law before the 1835 Texas Revolution shows cause-effect progression.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Create a timeline with key political events and write brief notes on Texican responses to each.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Ignoring the sequence of events can obscure understanding of political causality.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p>"
